GEP Qi Studio is an agent platform for designing, configuring, and executing workflow-based AI agents. It provides a visual builder for agent orchestrations, tool integration, and real-time execution with streaming feedback.
Agent developers who need to build, iterate, and run reliable AI workflows without managing the underlying runtime mechanics.

Build agent orchestrations using a drag-and-drop workflow canvas. Configure nodes for LLMs, tools, rules, guardrails, and nested workflows. Manage tools via MCP servers and system tool catalogs. Execute workflows with live streaming and human-in-the-loop (HITL) interrupts. Work across clients, domains, environments, apps, and modules.
New to the platform: Start with getting-started. Building a workflow: See build/canvas and build/nodes/index. Running workflows: See run/execution and run/streaming.
The canvas is the primary workspace for building workflow agents.

Node tray: browse available nodes and tools. Canvas toolbar: save, run, and toggle visibility options. Property panel: configure selected node properties. Code panel: inspect the underlying workflow JSON.
Auto-save at intervals for active workflows Undo/redo history tracking Alignment guides when dragging nodes Quick-fit and auto-layout controls
Open Agents in the left navigation. Click Create. Provide a name and description. Save to open the workflow canvas.
If you need a lightweight agent for direct LLM interactions, create a quantum agent and configure instructions, tools, and model settings.

Nodes are the building blocks of an agentic workflow. Each node has a type, configuration, and optional state updates. This section explains the common schema and then dives into each node type in detail.

Every node shares a common shape. The config field is type-specific, and the rest is consistent across the workflow. { "id": "string", "type": "start | llm | agent | tool | api | rule | guardrail | variable | script | iterator | parallel | workflow | output", "name": "string", "description": "string", "config": { "typeSpecific": "..." }, "variableUpdates": [ { "fieldName": "flow.someVar", "operation": "set | merge | append | extend | prepend | increment | decrement | clear", "value": "any", "condition": "{{optional.condition}}", "transform": { "type": "uppercase | lowercase | trim | json_parse | json_stringify | extract_field | format_date | custom" }, "role": "user | assistant | system | tool" } ] }

Config is per node type. The fields inside config are validated by the runtime for that node type. variableUpdates run after node execution. Use them to move node outputs into flow.*, system.*, threads.*, or nodes.*. Template resolution is supported. Most fields accept {{}} templates that resolve against state at runtime.
Node configs and variable updates commonly reference: flow.* for workflow state system.* for runtime metadata threads.* for conversation threads nodes.* for node outputs (nodes.<nodeId>.<field>)

Edges connect nodes. Some nodes produce dynamic outputs that change routing: Rule nodes route by ruleId (source handles use ruleId values and r-else). API and Guardrail nodes typically use pass / fail outputs.

The UI exposes some nodes that are still marked beta or not yet implemented in the runtime. The current engine supports these core types at runtime: start, llm, agent, tool, api, rule, workflow, output (and end as an alias of output) Nodes like variable, script, iterator, and parallel are present in the UI but may require additional runtime support depending on your deployment. Each node page calls this out explicitly.
The Agent node runs an autonomous agent that can call tools and iterate until it produces a final answer.
Multi-step reasoning (ReAct) with tool calling. Structured output when you need a strict response schema. Conversation management with per-agent threads.
You need the model to decide which tools to call. The task is ambiguous and requires multiple steps. You need tool execution history captured in outputs.

agentStrategy: react or function_calling model: same structure as the LLM node promptTemplate: array of messages (system/user/assistant/tool) tools: list of embedded tool definitions maxIterations: max tool/LLM steps (1-20) includeThoughts: include reasoning in output (if supported)

Each tool in tools includes: name, description config.type: mcp | api | code | custom | handoff config.settings: provider settings (e.g., MCP server id) config.parameters: input parameters (auto or static) config.schema: JSON schema for tool parameters Output controls: captureRawResponse: stores raw tool output in state llmProjection: filters which fields the LLM can see returnDirect: interrupts the workflow and returns tool output directly

Agent nodes emit a fixed payload: text: final response structuredOutput: when enabled toolCalls: list of tool invocations toolResults: captured raw tool outputs (when enabled) threadUpdate: persisted into thread.<agentId>_messages

{ "type": "agent", "config": { "agentStrategy": "react", "model": { "provider": "openai", "code": "gpt-4.1" }, "promptTemplate": [ { "id": "sys-1", "role": "system", "text": "You are a support agent." }, { "id": "usr-1", "role": "user", "text": "{{system.userQuery}}" } ], "tools": [ { "name": "search_kb", "description": "Search internal knowledge base", "config": { "type": "mcp", "settings": { "serverId": "kb-server" }, "schema": { "type": "object", "properties": { "query": { "type": "string" } }, "required": ["query"] }, "parameters": { "query": { "auto": true, "value": { "type": "string", "value": "" } } }, "captureRawResponse": true } } ], "maxIterations": 5 } }

The agent keeps its own thread at thread.<agentId>_messages. System prompts are not stored in the thread. returnDirect: true tools trigger a workflow interrupt and return tool output as the response. Keep maxIterations low to avoid runaway loops. Tools must be validated; invalid schemas or missing settings cause runtime failures.
The HTTP Request node (type: api) makes a direct HTTP call and exposes success/failure routing.
Call external services via REST. Branch workflow on success or fail. Use templates in URL, headers, body, and timeout.

Supported fields: method: GET | POST | PUT | PATCH | DELETE | HEAD | OPTIONS url: required, supports {{}} templates headers: JSON string, supports templates inside values body: JSON string (used for POST/PUT/PATCH) timeout: number (ms) or string template { "type": "api", "config": { "method": "POST", "url": "https://api.example.com/tickets", "headers": "{\"Authorization\":\"Bearer {{credentials.support.token}}\"}", "body": "{\"title\":\"{{flow.title}}\",\"priority\":\"{{flow.priority}}\"}", "timeout": 15000 } }
The node emits: success: boolean body: parsed response body (JSON when applicable) status_code headers error (present on failures)
Use SUCCESS and FAIL handles (pass/fail) in the canvas to branch on success.
URL must be valid http or https. headers and body must be valid JSON strings at design time. Timeouts are clamped by the runtime (min 1000 ms, max 30000 ms).
The Guardrail node runs safety or compliance checks on inputs or outputs. It can flag or sanitize content before downstream nodes consume it.
Run PII, jailbreak, or custom prompt checks. Optionally sanitize input text and write it back to state. Route to pass/fail branches.

Key fields: input: string template (e.g., {{flow.userMessage}}) checks: list of checks with name, stage, and params decision.mode: currently all_must_pass model: used for LLM-based checks (credentials injected at runtime) { "type": "guardrail", "config": { "input": "{{flow.userMessage}}", "checks": [ { "name": "PII", "stage": "input", "params": { "action": "mask" } }, { "name": "Jailbreak", "stage": "input", "params": { "model": { "code": "gpt-4.1", "provider": "openai" } } } ], "decision": { "mode": "all_must_pass" } } }
The node emits: passed: boolean sanitizedInput: string (when a check rewrites input) findings: list of violations rawGuardrailResults: raw check responses
Guardrail nodes are typically connected with PASS and FAIL handles.

LLM-based checks (e.g., CustomPrompt, Jailbreak) require a model in params.model. If sanitizedInput is returned, the node overwrites the input variable it read from. Guardrails require valid credentials injected at runtime, similar to LLM nodes.
The Iterator node is intended to loop over a list and run a set of nodes for each item.
Apply a sub-graph to each element in an array. Accumulate results back into state.

Iterator behavior is currently beta and evolving. Typical configuration may include: listPath: the state path to iterate (e.g., flow.items) itemVar: variable name to expose each item to the loop resultPath: where to store the collected results concurrency: optional parallelism limit
Runtime support may not be enabled in all deployments. Prefer a Workflow node if you need a stable, reusable loop pattern today. Be explicit about inputs and outputs to avoid large state growth.
The LLM node runs a single model call. Use it for deterministic generation, classification, or structured extraction.
Generates text from a prompt template. Optionally enforces a structured JSON response schema. Does not call tools (use Agent nodes for tool use).
You want a single-step LLM output. You do not need multi-step reasoning or tool calls. You need predictable output and lower latency than agent loops.

The model object follows ModelConfig and supports provider-specific settings: provider: openai | anthropic | azureopenai | local code: primary model identifier (preferred) name: display name (fallback) version: optional version label credentialId: references stored credentials temperature, maxTokens, topP, frequencyPenalty, presencePenalty
promptTemplate is required and must contain at least one message: { "id": "uuid", "role": "system | user | assistant | tool", "text": "string with {{variable}} references" }
Use structuredOutput.enable = true with a JSON schema to enforce output shape.
The LLM node returns a fixed payload: text: the generated text structuredOutput: present when structured output is enabled nodeId, nodeType

{ "type": "llm", "config": { "model": { "provider": "openai", "code": "gpt-4.1", "temperature": 0.2, "maxTokens": 1024 }, "promptTemplate": [ { "id": "sys-1", "role": "system", "text": "You are a concise assistant." }, { "id": "usr-1", "role": "user", "text": "Summarize {{flow.documentText}}." } ], "structuredOutput": { "enable": true, "name": "Summary", "description": "Document summary and key points", "schema": { "type": "object", "properties": { "summary": { "type": "string" }, "keyPoints": { "type": "array", "items": { "type": "string" } } }, "required": ["summary"] } } } }

promptTemplate is required; an empty template fails validation. Avoid high temperatures when you need deterministic structured output. Streaming can be enabled in config, but downstream nodes still receive the final payload.
The Output node ends the workflow and constructs the final response payload.
Terminate workflow execution. Map internal state to a clean response object. Optionally format or aggregate results.

Primary field: outputMapping: object of keys to typed values or templates The runtime expects typed values when outputMapping is produced by the schema converter: { "type": "output", "config": { "outputMapping": { "message": { "type": "string", "value": "{{flow.responseText}}" }, "confidence": { "type": "number", "value": "{{flow.confidence}}" }, "metadata": { "source": { "type": "string", "value": "llm" } } } } }
The node emits: output: final response object nodeId, nodeType
type: end is treated the same as type: output in the runtime.
Output nodes do not allow outgoing edges. Use outputMapping to ensure a stable API contract for callers. Template values that do not resolve fall back to literal values.
The Parallel node is intended to run multiple branches at the same time and then aggregate results.
Reduce latency by running independent tasks concurrently. Combine outputs for downstream decision-making.

Parallel behavior is currently beta and evolving. Typical configuration may include: branches: list of node ids or sub-graphs to execute joinStrategy: how to merge results (e.g., merge, collect) timeout: optional maximum duration
Runtime support may not be enabled in all deployments. Parallelism can increase load on tool and model quotas. Always define clear merge behavior to avoid ambiguous outputs.
The Rule node evaluates conditions and routes execution to the first matching rule.
Express conditional logic without code. Route to different branches based on state. Provide a default fallback route.

Rules are evaluated in order. The first rule that matches wins. { "type": "rule", "config": { "rules": [ { "ruleId": "r-high-priority", "enable": true, "logicType": "AND", "conditions": [ { "field": "{{flow.priority}}", "operator": ">=", "value": 8 }, { "field": "{{flow.status}}", "operator": "is", "value": "open" } ] }, { "ruleId": "r-default", "enable": true, "logicType": "default", "conditions": [] } ] } }

Supported operators include: String: contains, not contains, is, is not, starts with, ends with, is empty, is not empty Number: =, !=, <, >, <=, >=, is empty, is not empty Array: contains, not contains, is empty, is not empty, starts with, ends with Object: is empty, is not empty Boolean: is, is not, =, !=
The Rule node emits: matchedRule: rule id (or r-else) ruleResult: boolean evaluationDetails: optional diagnostics
Edges should use the rule id in their source handle: sourceHandle = ruleId for matched rules sourceHandle = r-else for the default path
Rule order matters. Place the most specific rules first. Use explicit namespaces (flow.*, system.*, nodes.*) to avoid ambiguity. logicType: default should be the last rule.
The Script node runs custom code (JavaScript, TypeScript, or Python) when declarative operations are insufficient.
Implement bespoke logic or calculations. Transform data into a custom output shape.

Typical fields include: language: javascript | typescript | python code: the script body inputs: named arguments (templated from state) { "type": "script", "config": { "language": "javascript", "code": "return { total: arg1 + arg2 };", "inputs": { "arg1": { "type": "number", "value": "{{flow.countA}}" }, "arg2": { "type": "number", "value": "{{flow.countB}}" } } } }
Script nodes typically return a json payload that can be mapped with variableUpdates.
Script node support is beta and may depend on runtime availability. Avoid accessing state directly inside the script; pass values through inputs. Keep scripts deterministic and side-effect free.
The Start node is the entry point for every workflow. It validates incoming inputs and signals that the workflow has begun.
Accepts runtime input (interface.inputs) and validates it. Does not mutate state directly. Emits a simple marker payload for downstream nodes to reference if needed.
Always include exactly one Start node at the top of a workflow. Use it to define which inputs are required and how they should be validated.

The Start node supports lightweight validation in config: requiredInputs: array of input field names that must be present. allowedInputs: array of input field names that are allowed (unexpected fields are logged as warnings). inputValidation: map of field names to validation rules (type, minLength, maxLength, pattern, enum). { "type": "start", "config": { "requiredInputs": ["query", "customerId"], "allowedInputs": ["query", "customerId", "locale"], "inputValidation": { "query": { "type": "string", "minLength": 1, "maxLength": 1000 }, "customerId": { "type": "string", "pattern": "^[A-Z0-9]+$" } } } }
The Start node emits a minimal payload into nodes.<startNodeId>: marker: "START" interface.inputs: the raw input object timestamp, nodeId, nodeType

Start does not update flow.* automatically. Use variableUpdates or a Variable node to copy inputs into state. Validation errors stop execution early, so keep rules aligned with your UI and API payloads. The Start node should not have incoming edges (see validation rules).
The Tool node runs a single tool definition (MCP, handoff, custom) as a standalone node.
Call a tool without involving an agent. Isolate tool execution and capture results in state. Use as a building block for deterministic flows.

The Tool node requires a toolDefinition in config. Key fields: id, name, description config.type: mcp | api | code | custom | handoff config.settings: provider configuration (e.g., MCP server id) config.parameters: tool inputs (can be templated) config.schema: JSON schema describing parameters { "type": "tool", "config": { "toolDefinition": { "id": "search_kb", "name": "Search KB", "description": "Search knowledge base", "config": { "type": "mcp", "settings": { "serverId": "kb-server" }, "parameters": { "query": { "auto": false, "value": { "type": "string", "value": "{{flow.query}}" } } }, "schema": { "type": "object", "properties": { "query": { "type": "string" } }, "required": ["query"] } } } } }
Tool nodes return: ok: success flag toolId, toolName, toolType result: tool output when successful error: error details when failed meta: tool-specific metadata
Tool nodes do not append messages to threads. Handoff tools can return a LangGraph Command and redirect execution. MCP tools require a valid serverId and accessible MCP server configuration.
The Variable node performs state mutations through a list of operations. It is useful for simple transformations and bookkeeping.
Update flow.*, threads.*, or nodes.* variables without scripts. Perform common operations such as set, merge, append, or clear.

The UI represents variable operations as a list in config.operations: { "type": "variable", "config": { "operations": [ { "fieldName": "flow.count", "operation": "increment", "value": 1 }, { "fieldName": "flow.tags", "operation": "append", "value": "priority" }, { "fieldName": "threads.main", "operation": "append", "role": "assistant", "value": "Hello!" } ] } } Supported operations include: set, merge, append, extend, prepend, increment, decrement, clear
Variable nodes do not produce outputs. They are used only for state mutation.

Variable node support is beta and may depend on runtime availability. Thread operations (threads.*) should include a role when appending messages. Prefer explicit field names with namespaces (flow.*, threads.*) to avoid ambiguity.
The Workflow node runs a child workflow with its own isolated state and returns the child output back to the parent.
Reuse complex flows as a single node. Encapsulate sub-logic and keep the parent workflow clean. Support interrupts from the child workflow.

Key fields: agenticWorkflowId: id of the child workflow agenticWorkflowIdMode: static or dynamic version: optional version (dynamic mode supports templating) inputs: mapping of parent state to child inputs childWorkflowSchema: attached by the runtime when using static mode { "type": "workflow", "config": { "agenticWorkflowId": "customer-support-flow", "inputs": { "query": "{{flow.customerQuery}}", "sessionId": "{{system.sessionId}}" } } }

The node returns: childGraphId, childSessionId /- Child output payload (from the child Output node) variables: the child workflow state snapshot Interrupt metadata when a child workflow pauses for input
If the child workflow interrupts (e.g., HITL), the parent Workflow node also interrupts. The interrupt metadata includes the child checkpoint id and session id required to resume execution.

In dynamic mode, the runtime needs configurable.workflowSchemaLoader to load the child schema at runtime. Inputs are resolved against the parent state at runtime; keep them explicit and minimal. The child output is taken from the child Output node after id transformation at compile time.

GEP Qi Studio enforces guardrails to keep workflows valid: Start nodes cannot be targets of incoming connections. Output nodes do not allow outgoing connections. Self-loops are not allowed. When designing workflows: Keep branching rules explicit. Place guardrails before output. Prefer named outputs for clarity.
GEP Qi Studio supports two primary agent experiences for developers:

Workflow agents are visual, node-based graphs you build on the canvas. They are ideal for: Multi-step reasoning and orchestration Tool calling and guardrails Conditional logic and branching Streaming outputs and HITL checkpoints
Quantum agents focus on direct LLM interactions with tools and instructions. They are typically used when you want a simpler agent definition without a full workflow graph.
Use workflow agents for complex orchestration, multi-step pipelines, or approvals. Use quantum agents for conversational or instruction-driven behavior that does not require a full graph.
Execution turns your workflow definition into a live run that processes inputs and produces outputs.
Design-time: create and update workflows and agent definitions. Runtime: execute compiled workflows, stream events, and handle interrupts.
During runtime, the platform emits events such as: Node start / node end Streaming text deltas Tool call events Workflow completion These events power the live UI and execution tracking.
Nodes are the building blocks of workflows. Each node performs a specific function and can emit output variables for downstream nodes.

Start: initializes workflow input. LLM: runs a large language model prompt. Agent: invokes another agent workflow. HTTP Request: calls external APIs. Tool: invokes a configured tool integration. Guardrail: safety or validation checks. Rule: conditional routing. Workflow: nested workflow execution. Script: custom script execution. Variable: set or transform variables. Iterator: loop over data sets. Parallel: run multiple branches simultaneously. Output: finalize and return results. Some node types may be hidden or marked beta based on your environment.
Each node declares output variables you can reference using {{variableName}} in downstream nodes.
Variables are the primary way data moves between nodes.
Use double curly braces to reference variables: {{variableName}}
Flow variables: scoped to a workflow execution. System variables: globally available and managed by the platform.
Use descriptive names to avoid collisions. Check node outputs to understand what variables are produced. Validate variables in guardrails or rules before using them in critical logic.
Workflows define how an agent runs from start to finish. A workflow is a directed graph of nodes (steps) and edges (connections).
Start node: entry point and input binding. Processing nodes: LLMs, tools, scripts, rules, or nested workflows. Output node: final result or response payload.
Edges determine execution order. Rules and guardrails add conditional branching. Nested workflows allow reuse and composition.
Build the workflow in the design-time UI. Compile and store the workflow for runtime execution. Execute the graph with inputs and receive streamed results.
Yes. Use the Workflow node to invoke an existing workflow as a nested step.
Use output variables from upstream nodes and reference them as {{variableName}}.

documents.s: Are all nodes available in every environment?

documents.t: This guide helps you access GEP Qi Studio, set up your environment context, and create your first agent workflow.

GEP Qi Studio uses separate tokens for design-time and runtime APIs: Design-time token: agent management and configuration. Runtime token: workflow execution and streaming. If tokens are missing or expired, the platform prompts for updates via the auth dialog and reloads after save.

Before any API calls can work, you must select a domain context: Client Domain (BPC code) Environment App Module If the platform detects a valid context in the URL, it hydrates the selection automatically. Otherwise, a forced modal prompts you to configure it before proceeding.

Open the Agents area. Click Create to start a new workflow agent. Use the canvas to add nodes, connect them, and configure properties. Save the workflow and run it with a sample input. Next: see build/canvas for a full walkthrough.

Agent orchestration: A workflow-based agent built on the visual canvas. Quantum agent: A lightweight agent centered around direct LLM interaction. Node: A single step in a workflow graph. Edge: A connection that defines execution flow between nodes. Domain context: The client/domain/environment/app/module selection that scopes all APIs. Design-time: The configuration layer for agents and tools. Runtime: The execution layer for workflows and streaming events. HITL: Human-in-the-loop interrupts that require user input. MCP: Model Context Protocol, used for dynamic tool discovery.
Once a workflow is saved, you can execute it directly from the canvas.

Open the workflow agent. Click Run to open the execution panel. Provide input and start the run. Review the live execution status and final output. Execution is tracked node-by-node so you can see where time is spent and where errors occur.
Some workflows can pause execution to request human input or approval.

A node triggers an interrupt and provides a form schema. The UI prompts you for required inputs. You choose to continue or stop the workflow. HITL helps implement approval gates, safety checks, and exception handling in critical workflows.
GEP Qi Studio uses server-sent events (SSE) to stream execution updates.
Live node start and completion highlights Incremental text output for LLM responses Tool call activity during execution
Streaming provides immediate feedback during long runs and makes debugging faster by showing where execution is spending time.

GEP Qi Studio uses two token types: Design-time token: used for agent management and configuration APIs. Runtime token: used for workflow execution and streaming APIs. Tokens are stored locally in the browser. When tokens expire, the platform prompts for updates and reloads the app after saving.
All API calls in GEP Qi Studio depend on a domain context. Without it, the platform blocks execution and configuration.
Client Domain (BPC code) Environment App Module

If a compact domain config is present in the URL, the platform hydrates it automatically. If not, a forced modal prompts you to select the required context before proceeding. This ensures every agent and tool configuration is scoped correctly.
Environments define where a workflow runs and which versions of apps/modules are active.

Use non-production environments for development and testing. Refresh module configuration when switching context. Align tool configurations with the selected environment. If you see inconsistent results, re-check the domain context and the selected module version.
MCP (Model Context Protocol) servers provide dynamic tool discovery. Once a server is configured, its tools become available to workflows.
Register an MCP server in the Tools area. Discover available tools from that server. Configure tool parameters per node. Use MCP when you want external tools to be managed and discovered at runtime.
Tools allow agents to access external capabilities such as APIs, services, or custom integrations.
MCP tools: discovered from registered MCP servers. System tools: platform-managed built-ins.
Tools are attached to tool-capable nodes. The configuration form is typically driven by a schema, so you can fill required fields without manual JSON edits.
System tools are built-in capabilities that are curated and maintained by the platform.
You need stable, supported integrations. You want tools that are governed by platform policies. System tools are typically available across environments and require less setup than custom MCP tools.
Ensure the URL contains a valid domain config. Re-select client/domain/environment/app/module and save.
Update the design-time and runtime tokens. Reload the page after saving tokens.
Confirm nodes are connected properly and include an Output node. Check for guardrails or rules that prevent progress. Verify tool configuration and environment context.
documents.s: Workflow does not run or stalls

documents.t: Ensure streaming is enabled in canvas preferences. Re-run the workflow to re-establish the SSE connection.
